Opaque types — zero-cost nominal wrappers.

Recall the two options from earlier notebooks. A type alias does not create a new type — it makes the alias and the underlying type completely interchangeable, so it documents intent but enforces nothing. A wrapper class does create a distinct type, but it allocates a wrapper object for every instance, which costs memory and indirection.

Opaque types are Scala 3's middle ground. An opaque type is a genuinely new, distinct type at compile time — the compiler refuses to mix it with the underlying type — but at runtime it is exactly the underlying type, with no boxing and no overhead at all.

The mechanism is scoping. You declare an opaque type inside an object. Inside that object, you can convert freely between the opaque type and its underlying representation, and you provide a constructor and any allowed operations there. Outside the object, the type is opaque — code cannot see through it to the underlying type. Picture an ids object defining a user-id and an account-id, both backed by string. Outside the object they are distinct types, so a function that expects a user-id accepts a user-id and rejects an account-id, even though both are strings underneath — the compiler enforces the separation. Yet at runtime each is just a string, with zero wrapper cost. That combination — real type safety at compile time, no runtime price — is what makes opaque types the right tool for domain types like ids, quantities, and units.
